{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0c3abec1-c4ce-475a-89cd-c5348a69a7a9","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **first-class implicit span conversions**. `T[]` now implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and that conversion is *more specific* than `T[]` → `IEnumerable<T>` in overload resolution.\n\nSo `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)   // ← C# 14\n```\n\ninstead of:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)           // ← C# 13\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it can't be captured in expression trees. The tree is built referencing a method the interpreter can't invoke, so it throws at runtime.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `IEnumerable<T>` overload:\n\n**Option A — cast the receiver:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither way you get the same `Enumerable.Contains<int>` `MethodCallExpression` you had on .NET 9, and the interpreter can handle it.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9f1e0e18-704d-4a9f-8929-acb8a7d7f7a7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to how the compiler resolves extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension members** (sometimes called \"extension everything\" or the new extension syntax), but more relevantly, there's a change in how `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains` vs array-specific methods are resolved.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is likely related 